<TITLE> Salam 'admits Aug 21 links' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 3 (bdnews24.com)Sheikh Abdus Salam, founder of the banned Harkat-ul-Jihad al Islami, has confessed his involvement in the Aug 21 2004 grenade attack on an Awami League procession, which killed at least 20 people, police said Thursday. The detained leader of the outlawed Islamist outfit gave his statement in a Dhaka court, where he was produced after 15 days of interrogation by CID. Metropolitan magistrate Moajjem Hossain heard the five-hour confessional statement, ending at 9pm, in his private chamber. Mohammad Abdul Haque, general recording officer at the court, told bdnews24.com that Salam was taken into the magistrate's chamber to record his confessional statement at around 4pm. Police officer of the court Anisur Rahman told bdnews24.com afterward: "Salam admitted his involvement in the grenade attack." Rahman gave no further details, but added that Salam was sent to jail again after the statement. Salam was arrested on Nov 2 in connection with the Aug 21 attack. At least 24 people, including Awami League leader Ivy Rahman, wife of president Zillur Rahman, lost their lives in the attack on a party rally at Bangabandhu Avenue in Dhaka. Scores sustained injuries, including prime minister Sheikh Hasina, then opposition leader. Twenty-two people were accused in the grenade attack case including BNP leader Abdus Salam Pintu and HuJI leader Mufti Hannan. Former BNP state minister for home, Lutfozzaman Babar, now in jail, has also been shown arrested in the case. bd
